Alternative 1: Queue-Based Management System
Instead of just open/close, implement a waiting queue:

How it works: If parking is full, vehicles queue for the next available spot
Advantages: Prevents wasted trips, better user experience

Instead of: Registration → Full? → Close Gate
Try: Registration → Full? → Add to Queue → Notify when spot available

Alternative 2: Multi-Level Priority System
Implement tiered access based on user type:

Levels: Staff (Priority 1) → Students (Priority 2) → Visitors (Priority 3)
Logic: If lot is nearly full, prevent lower-priority vehicles but allow higher priority
Benefits: Ensures staff always have spots, optimizes resource allocation

Alternative 3: Real-Time Capacity Estimation
Add predictive logic:

Track: Entry/exit patterns over time
Predict: When parking will fill up
Action: Pre-route vehicles to alternate lots
Implementation: Simple averaging of historical data

Real World Implementation

Arduino Solution (Simplest)
Cost: ~$80 | Complexity: Low
Core: Arduino Uno + RFID reader (vehicle ID) + ultrasonic sensor (count cars) + servo motor (open barrier) + LCD display (show spots)
Data: Store registration & count on SD card or cloud
Process: Scan ID → Check database → Count cars → Open/Close gate
Best for: Single gate, university campus
Raspberry Pi Solution (Balanced)

Cost: ~$120 | Complexity: Medium
Core: Raspberry Pi 4 + camera (vehicle detection) + relay module (motor control) + local database
Data: SQLite database runs locally, tracks registrations & occupancy
Process: Camera detects vehicle → Python checks registration → Updates count → Controls barrier
Best for: Multiple gates, analytics needed

Cloud IoT Solution (Professional)
Cost: ~$300+ | Complexity: High
Core: IoT device (Arduino/Pi) + AWS/Azure cloud + mobile app
Data: Cloud database syncs across multiple locations
Process: Device sends data → Cloud processes → Real-time updates to app/dashboard
Best for: Large campuses, multi-gate systems, remote management
